ODE III.

This ode commences with an encomium on justice and con- stancy3 and shows that many mortals have, by these virtueS, gained admission to the assembly of the gods. But its main object was to discourage the plan of making Troy, instead of Rome, the seat of the empire, which Augustus was supposed to be meditating. A design of this sort was generally believed to have been formed by Julius Caesar, a short time before his assassination 3 and Augustus seemed disposed to carry out the projects of his predecessor.
